Duel of the last blood: MP3 players versus cell phones
We will advise you on how to choose
While almost every cell phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
It is clear from this that it is better to buy only the phone.
Nevertheless, there are many reasons for acquiring a standalone reader.
The choice depends entirely on the use and the needs of the future owner.
You might not buy an expensive high-quality record player to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc album.
First of all, these musical products are not released as LP's and there is no objective reason for this from a qualitative point of view.
But if your shelves are crammed with hard-rock, jazz or blues, you probably dream of a record player like this.
It also works with portable music, i.e. music in a compact format or simply in MP3 format.
Here too, there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend 8,000 crowns on a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan may find it difficult to digest the 20-crown headphones on the market.
Two extremes between which there's enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It's the battery life that determines.
Some high-quality music players can do much more than simply read music, something that mobile phones do not even accidentally do.
There is no other device today as universal as the mobile phone.
Besides the basic functions, calling and texting, it can read music and video, record both, and it has a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse, and maybe even navigate.
And if you take smartphones and handhelds into account, you'll also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It's a small miracle, because no refrigerator can make a grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your phone, the sooner the indicator on the screen will require charging.
And reading music takes a lot of energy.
Few phones can read music for more than 12 hours, usually, and much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more effective.
As for cheap cell phones, don't count on them lasting more than a few hours.
If you add a few more calls from time to time, get another charger at work for safety reasons, even for the most expensive appliances.
But you won't have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst ones last at least nine hours of continuous playback on a single charge.
Another problem arises when music is downloaded into a mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have the universal USB port, and not all can be connected to a computer without special software.
Music can certainly be recorded directly to the memory card, but only a few memory players are able to do so without the mini-card adapter that is not used in mobile phones.
Readers, with a few exceptions (iPods), do not need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from the computer.
Most mobile phones and players create a multimedia library of their own, sorted by the names of the performers, the name of the album, the genre or the user's classification.
Some devices only reproduce the tree structure of the folders, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to use, cell phones can do more.
When choosing a particular device, you should be especially concerned with battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of audio output, and clearly ease of use.
If you want music mostly as a background and if you listen to it every day just briefly on the tram, you just need any MP3 player phone.
This is now clearly possible on any mobile phone.
You don't have to worry too much about what formats your phone or your reader recognizes.
MP3 players support all of them, so the majority of the music that you get will be in this format.
In addition to this format, which is one of the most common, the vast majority of devices support music in WMA format.
The AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods) is missing.
The best cell phones also allow you, for example, to buy music online.
You just have to visit the corresponding pages of the operator (or another provider) via the mobile internet network and buy the song or album.
This service itself could be a good reason to buy a mobile phone reader.
Unfortunately, the offer of the operators is meager and is usually limited to the hits of the moment on the radio.
The prices are not very low.
But it is generally assumed that this very mode of selling music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their cell phones with them.
Anyone who wants to listen to something, just grab it in their pocket and leave the MP3 player at home.
But it also depends on whether you always carry your headphones or at least your wireless earbuds.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every cell phone, but only a small portion of MP3 players, has.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of mobile phone readers will be, for many, the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000 crowns.
For three or four thousand crowns you'll already buy a very decent walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the lack of an entrance for the common headphones.
The best and most technically equipped cell phones, and even with the 3.5 mm socket for ordinary headphones, cost up to 15 thousand crowns.
The advantage of the readers is, among other things, the ease of use.
The simpler ones, not necessarily the cheaper ones (see our selection), are really handy for anyone to handle.
The minimal features, the similarity of the handling once with the common stereo or perhaps the record player, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally hitting the mobile internet start-up and consequently a huge data transmission bill.
What device to take
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (M2, microSD, etc.).
The purchase of the card is also included in the 2 000 SEK.
But be careful
The basic models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones can even do it with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a cell phone and you want to buy a cheap MP3 player, go to Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton, or whatever.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1 100 kroner.
If you are among the most demanding listeners, you may prefer to buy specialized walk-man phones (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have individual MP3 keys and the convenience of the service thus approaches the same MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson has come a long way in this area, with the walkman line of phones having the same usage scale as MP3 players sold separately.
The MP3 players of the above brands provide the same service and price category up to SEK 4 000, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (commonly 15 hours, generally up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Maybe I should .
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all the services as their Western European counterparts.
However, there is something missing here: a virtual operator that forces the traditional ones to lower their prices.
Maybe he won't be gone for long.
We have already written many times on Mobil.cz about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was confirmed by ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in the EU than in the rest of the EU.
After the latest steps by the European Commission in the field of roaming tariff regulation, a paradoxical situation may arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS will cost less abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to start the fight.
This may sound absurd, but we have three mobile networks here, and coverage is well over 100%.
On the other hand, mobile telephony operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
This is also often emphasised by the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, who has sometimes expressed in the past that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network probably no longer has many possibilities (and it would probably be difficult to find other frequencies).
But there is another possibility - the virtual operator.
The very entry of virtual operators into the market led to a significant price reduction, to which traditional operators would have had to react.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, similar voices were sounding in Britain as we are.
But it has been shown that there is a place for such operators and that they can be really successful.
We do not have to go very far in the example.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the Mobilking virtual operator in Poland.
In just six months, the operator has managed to win over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which in the Czech Republic is owned by U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is that they can concentrate on a much more concrete target group.
In order to operate effectively, it needs far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
There are no relatively high costs involved in setting up, operating and maintaining the mobile network.
So in the world, virtual operators usually come in cheap, offering cheap calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the more restricted offer of services.
So for example Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS that costs at least half of its competitors.
But as Mobilking's example in Poland shows, betting on a not-so-small-handed group can also be a pretty good move.
This operator is aiming, so to speak, specifically at men.
"Real men choose a Mobilking operator that they like and can trust", says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can say the same as in Poland.
Vodafone's press spokesman Miroslav Čepický doubts this: 'The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, which is the basis for most virtual operators.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of services".
No chance in the Czech Republic, say mobile operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is ever an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"There is talk of expanding this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very hopeful.
The activation of Mobilking will rather take place in other countries in our area", said Jana Studničková, the press spokesperson for the financial group Penta, in a telephone conversation with Mobile.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are not very supportive of this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything because it creates no potential competitor.
For some time now, it has been keen to launch a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group, which would like to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them,' says Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
So maybe better times are coming.
The first virtual operator is expected to be available by the end of the year, according to unofficial information.
But for now, an impenetrable wall of silence is building around his creation.
'At the moment we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a fully-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no one with a complex and serious project has come to us", said Vlastimil Sršeň of the press section of Telefónica O2 in a statement to Mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is also used by other operators.
T-Mobil press spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: 'At the moment we have not noticed any viable and mutually beneficial commercial project on which it is possible to continue building.'
He adds: 'It is unlikely that a virtual operator will appear on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point we should have had a concrete agreement on the table so that it could be considered on the horizon.'
Vodafone concentrates its attention rather on meeting its own 3G licence requests.
Miroslav Čepický adds: 'We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the customer's point of view, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for high-speed mobile internet".
Competent authorities - with the accomplices
The attitude of mobile operators is easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profits.
Why, then, facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The problems surrounding the creation of U:fon are evidence that when operators care about one thing they know how to row in the same direction.
Perhaps the great pressure was on ČTÚ during the period of U:fon's creation towards the T-Mobile company.
This is evidenced by the publicly available information on the ČTÚ web pages.
But now U:fon is the argument against accepting the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová observed: 'The competitive environment in the mobile telephony market has recently been strengthened, above all with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place high demands on it and especially on its services.'
The attitude of mobile operators is, however, surprising in that the Czech regulatory authorities are completely disinterested.
It is not just the attitude of the CTU, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere with economic competition.
That is the exclusive responsibility of the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This is a very important point.
'The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after the conclusion of the lease agreement for the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers was probably not attractive enough for traditional operators", said Kristián Chalupa, of the ÚOHS's external relations section, in response to our question.
This statement by the representatives of the operators is perhaps not surprising.
The Commission has not yet decided on the proposal for a directive on the protection of consumers' rights.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Outside the country where virtual operators commonly operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephony services".
But of course pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and price reduction are not in ÚOHS' interests.
What is really shocking about the whole situation is the almost emotional harmony of these three actors resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence arises on its own.
Like the fact that the price of petrol is the same for all petrol stations, it is certainly the result of coincidence and competition.
'The Chamber has not found any evidence of anti-competitive behaviour in this respect and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position and therefore no correspondingly greater responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The telecommunications regulator may also lack the tools necessary to open up the mobile network market to virtual operators,' Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of market dominance is one of the many controversial issues .
Of course, there is the analysis of the relevant markets by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - the agreement of the network operator is always necessary for the creation of a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator has, after all, logically, a monopoly on its network.
So for a certain portion it has to be dominant.
But even if we did not admit this argument, it should be a warning sign for ÚOHS that three mobile operators are proceeding in such a strangely similar way.
At the same time, the complaints from interested parties (including the aforementioned GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all operators.
The fact that the responsibility for telecommunications is transferred to ČTÚ is a common trick by which ÚOHS keeps itself out of the whole affair.
We have seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the extension of ČTÚ's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications was not promoted until the recent update of the Telecommunications Act, despite the fact that many experts expected this to improve the situation.
The representatives of the Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights must be well aware of this fact, but perhaps their interests lie elsewhere.
You can do it when no one's watching
We do not see the operation of these pseudo-virtual operators, some of which even exist in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies which publish their own price lists for mobile telephony services, but these are only partially public.
These are usually companies that do multi-level marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the people who have been appointed.
The magic is that the company is represented to the operator as a classic corporate customer, ordering a large number of SIM cards.
How a major customer then gets special price offers (and so on).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a pre-sale.
"If the cases you mention, which we will be interested in, arise, it could be a breach of the contractual terms and could lead to the termination of cooperation with this company", Martina Kemrová answered the question in question.
But it is unlikely that such activity would not reach the ears of the responsible parties of the mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned above, there may be thousands of customers.
No operator is simultaneously defending itself against such an attitude.
The Commission has also taken the view that the Commission should be able to take a decision on the basis of the information provided by the Member States.
Miroslav Čepický warns of potential problems: "The law allows for such speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot have it in full as regular customers of mobile operators do.
But that's what should be a little strange at ČTU.
In addition, another issue arises for ÚOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to this attitude, why are they blocking the creation of the virtual operator?
It should be added that ÚOHS has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if it does not want to it will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of operators who have no idea of all this and whose commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we 're not more expensive
As has been stated several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile telephony market has led to a significant reduction in the prices of services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where operators were born, traditional operators were more or less trying to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were almost identical - market too small, the threshold too saturated, problems with quality of service, etc.
But in developed countries, regulatory bodies have intervened in these cases to protect not mobile operators but their customers.
Both formal measures and informal pressure led to the creation of the first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities are throwing themselves at each other like a hot potato all the time.
In our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of competence in these cases makes them more than comfortable.
But let's not give up.
If the background information is correct and the virtual operator really appears soon, the Czech mobile market will get back on track.
If one of the operators had agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, ÚOHS could hardly remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of the other operators concerned.
And maybe we'll stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem "Kde domov můj" in a solemn way on the occasion of the Czech State's Day of Recognition.
The new recording of the anthem was made by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available  solo with male or female vocals, choral pass and instrumental editing.
The song is under the direction of Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the revisions of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz website you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national anthem to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
He has already told the radio "Český rozhlas" that he has chosen specially to sing the solo variants, the singers with the most representative young voices, which are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried to make sure that both the choir and the singers had clear diction, that the lyrics were clear, that they were in harmony", he said.
Then the national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song "Kde domov můj" was first performed in 1834 on the stage of the Stavovskéh divadlo in the original Fidlovačka opera by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by music by František Škroupa.
It gained popularity and people spontaneously made it their own.
The first verse of the song after the founding of Czechoslovakia in 1918 then became the natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the birth of the autonomous Czech Republic.
