The MHD Wednesday in Prague will also accompany you for the first time with an electronic card
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will go down in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers on the subway, tram and bus will have an electronic ticket in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
Right now , it 's available to about 100,000 people who have their own Opencard .
Passengers can buy the 30-day and 90-day and annual (starting from 1 January 2009) and at the same time have their card recharged at the Infopoint and the offices of the Transport Company and at the Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stops.
The coupons can be purchased from yesterday on the Internet on the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than 400 customers before noon.
Those who start using the service via the Internet can completely forget about the ticket counters at subway stations where they used to have to wait in long lines for paper tickets.
The ticket is purchased online and uploaded to one of the twelve branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places passengers have a trained desk staff that will help them with their internet purchases and will also record the credit on their card", said project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition, in libraries it will be possible to load the electronic vouchers onto the Opencard ATMs and self-service machines installed at the metro entrances.
What are these ATMs like?
They are red, resemble ticket obliterators and passengers have already noticed them at the metro stops Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are now five in the whole city but by the end of the year there should be 80", concluded Opatrný.
The ticket will be checked by the ATM instead of the driver.
The ATM service that will be running from tomorrow is very simple.
Just put in your Opencard card and after paying the coupon, it will be loaded on top.
Electronic cards are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
This is the case on the urban train and bus lines from 300 to 499, which the inhabitants of the municipalities of Central Bohemia take to reach the capital.
"In the trains added to Prague's integrated transport there are card readers to check the time and zone validity", explained the ticket checking method of Filip from the Ropid organisation, which sets Prague's public transport schedules.
City buses have card readers integrated into the driver's trunk.
During the climb it is therefore necessary not only to show the magnetic card to the driver, but also to place the Opencard at the specified point next to the cash register.
The driver checks the validity of the loaded coupons.
"If the passenger needs to check the validity of the loaded coupons, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this kind of information", Drápal added.
Passengers who take the city bus and do not remember when the ticket expires can go back to the self-service ATMs, where the ticket is loaded onto the card.
Here, information on the validity of their documents will be displayed on the device's screen.
The Sudeten Germans wanted a referendum from the US
The Sudeten Germans in 1945 asked to include Šumava in the United States.
This is according to the letter deposited in the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live at least under the patronage of the United States.
With this desire, it is said, some groups of Sudeten Germans addressed the President of the United States in 1945.
This is also evident from the letter kept in a private archive and now deposited in the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Czechs in Český Krumlov ask the American president not to allow the return of the "Sumava district"  occupied by Hitler under the Munich Agreement  to Czechoslovakia.
"We understand the situation and want to be sure of the promises that American units will arrive on German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators", the letter, signed "People who hold the fate of Šumava with all their hearts", reads.
Since, they say, the annexation of Czechoslovakia - knowing the Czech national character - gives the Sudeten Germans hope only in brutality, lack of regard, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter beg the American president to assume the protectorate of Šumava now and forever.
