The exploit in the second quarter is a team record.
After spending more time than anyone else in the Jets uniform for the past eight and more seasons, defensive back Shaun Ellis thought he'd seen it all.
Then he watched the second quarter unfold on Sunday, when the Jets turned a scoreless game into a comeback.
"Never seen anything like it", said Ellis.
The second quarter began after the Jets and Arizona Cardinals had equaled the gray of the menacing clouds overhead with a feeble game.
Then quarterback Brett Favre found Laveranues Coles for a 12-yard touchdown, providing the perfect signal for an afternoon when their growing synchronization took a giant leap forward.
Favre found Coles for two more touchdowns in the fourth, including one when a cornerback fell and another with 10 seconds left in the first half.
"I didn't go out of my way", said Favre of all the passages that came to Coles.
He's a great player.
Our communication was great, despite what people may think".
As Favre and Coles played catch, the defense hit Cardinals quarterback Kurt Warner hard.
Cornerback Darrelle Revis intercepted a running play and returned it 32 yards for a touchdown.
Eric Smith's security team predicted another pass and intercepted it.
Linebacker David Bowens is forcing a fumble from Warner.
The last turnover, the fumble forced by Bowens, may have been the most remarkable.
The Cardinals took the lead on that possession with 10 seconds left, and after the Jets had taken the ball with 10 minutes left, Jay Feely kicked a 20-yard field goal to give them a 34-0 lead.
That's more than the Jets have ever scored in a quarter.
When asked to describe the insanity, Jets coach Eric Mangini said, "The second quarter or the third quarter?"
When told both - the Jets gave up 21 unanswered points in the third quarter - Mangini said, "I can tell you that I liked the second quarter a lot more than the third".
There were a lot of points in a short time".
Gebrselassie rested and beat his world record
Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia showed again why many consider him the best marathon runner ever, breaking his own world record at the Berlin Marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to run a 26.2 mile run under 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With a win on the favourably flat course in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie shatters his previous score of 2:03:26 set last year in Berlin by 27 seconds.
At 35, Gebrselassie sets the 26th world record in a career so stunning that it has produced a world championship or a world record at every distance from the metric mile to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Beijing Olympics marathon, fearing - perhaps too alarmingly, in retrospect - that air pollution would worsen his asthma problems.
Instead, he decided to run to Berlin.
In near-perfect conditions - sunny and 48 degrees at the start, 55 degrees at the finish - Gebrselassie won Sunday with a scorching average of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
As long-distance runners like Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya have gone the distance, the marathon record has fallen by more than two minutes in the past decade since Ronaldo of Costa do Brasil won in Berlin in 2:06:05 in 1998.
After his victory on Sunday, Gebrselassie told reporters that two weeks ago he had calf cramps and missed a week of training.
Clearly, the rest has left him fresh, not rusty.
"I'm so happy", Gebrselassie told reporters, "I'm not going to be able to do it".
"Everything was perfect.
I started again a week ago, and I had doubts today, but in the end it all worked out".
He has been somewhat criticized - especially in Kenya, Ethiopia's East African rival - for over-orchestrating his races, generally avoiding many of the world's top marathon stars, relying on the runway as if it were a half-long race, and putting world records above the sense of competition.
But these criticisms rarely diminish the magnitude of Gebrselassie's skills as a marathon runner.
With the pace accelerated by four Kenyans on Sunday, Gebrselassie reached the halfway point in 1:02:04.
Two Kenyan elite runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, held Gebrselassie after the opening laps were wiped out.
Just over three miles from the finish, Gebrselassie made a steep final to part with Kwambai, who finished second in 2:05:36, improving his personal best time by almost 5 minutes.
Kamathi came in third in 2:07:48.
In the women's race, Irina Mikitenko, a native of Kazakhstan who is now a German citizen, completed a remarkable year by winning in 2:19:19, the seventh fastest time ever.
Paula Radcliffe of Great Britain holds the world record of 2:15:25.
Last spring, Mikitenko, 36, was a surprise winner of the London Marathon in 2:24:14.
She missed the Beijing Games in what is described as a bad accident, but recovered to win in Berlin, setting her personal best time of almost five minutes in the third marathon she ran.
She ran a race doing the math, letting a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners start at a great distance, taking them back after about 18 and a half miles.
Askale Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second in 2:21.31, while Helena Kiprop of Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
In a city apart, pride and trials of a black life
Hidden in the sprawling theme park in the suburbs of Orlando, just a few miles from the glitter, the noise, the enormity, lies the quiet city where the pride and the complications of the African-American experience come into life.
Eatonville, the first all-black incorporated city in the country and the birthplace of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, abundance of guava, two schools and no prison".
It's a place of pilgrimage now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! festival in Eatonville to pay their respects to Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
Yet in many ways, the city he described - and which makes tourists stop by including it in the Florida tour guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers' Project - remains a place apart.
It is as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, that "knowing so little about us, he does not know what he is missing".
Even now, in a year when a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, has been called in for a keynote address on race, many here remain wary of the outsider's gaze.
"We are very careful about how our story is told", said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city's oldest church.
"It must be right".
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It's both a historic model of black power grab and a community of nearly 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It's a literary center but also an example of the oak shade of rural Southern black culture - sometimes scorned, sometimes rewarded - born of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the residents here are both proud and protective.
And the concern for Eatonville's image really started with Zora, who everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through candid, dialect-rich books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida guide transformed the city, just off Route 17, a road that runs through the often forgotten center of Florida into a setting of black history and human drama.
Low as a bucket in both life and literature, Hurston took readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then veered off into more private areas.
"Off the street to the left", he wrote, "is the modern public school, brown with white finishes, with its well-kept gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always tended, thinking he could scarcely read and write".
She also mentioned the widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of drinks and anything that fits the passing rooms".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, second marriages and sex.
Clearly this wasn't Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone liked.
"Zora told it like it was", said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson's girlfriends whom Hurston immortalized by quoting men who sing coarse songs about their beauty.
He adds: "Some people don't like it".
Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who frequently returned from her relocated family to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalls that when Hurston drove into the city, he usually arrived unannounced in a triumphant Chevrolt, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still boasts decent clothing.
Many residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin says, while others grinned.
"People were always very glad to see Zora", said Mr. Franklin.
But, she added, rocking in her chair on the back patio overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed long".
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books had gone out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no big memorial ceremonies, and no big conferences.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy to everyone", said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a 2003 biography of Hurston.
A change occurred in the 1980's.
Orange County officials wanted to place a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the two-lane main road.
Orlando's expansion has already pushed Interstate 4 through the city's western border.
The proposal came as Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration had, among other things, brought an end to the community's idyllic isolation.
In the 1950s, the battle over racial mixing brought hate to the community's doorstep.
"During that time, a group of white boys came and threw oranges and things at people sitting on one side", says Mr. Franklin.
"We actually had a girl who got killed by that one time.
They threw a watermelon out of a car".
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston petitioned the Supreme Court for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown v. Board of Education "an insult rather than an honor to my race".
Residents now say that the desegregation of schools, while positive in some respects, is diluting Eatonville's cohesion and jeopardizing the confidence of its youth.
"Black kids used to be hugged - I remember this - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening", said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a nonprofit group.
This lasted, he added, until teachers and students came from the same place.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because your white teacher... - I mean, there's a cultural divide there", said Mrs. Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, helped and made room for many more Zora Neale Hurstons - black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudice, as she did, with cheerful self-assurance and lines like, "How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I just can't understand it".
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long journey to the unmarked grave of Hurston and began to fight for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway hit the bookshelves, reintroducing it into the American canon.
The highway project came just as his most famous daughter had re-turned the spotlight.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning in 1988 a festival dedicated to Hurston to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state backed down from its road project.
"The five lanes of the revived highway, brought what would be called high speed, a real pride for the city", Ms. Nathiri said.
Mrs. Boyd put it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville".
The victory over the highway project helped change the image the city has of itself.
Out-of-towners like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started coming to church here in 1993, started showing up in large numbers, and residents started reevaluating the past.
Eatonville was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1998.
A new one-story bookstore (called Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a repainted and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly in Florida: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can feel like a side street in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It's 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to search for the history of Eatonville, for its significance, are often still treated with caution.
Prior permission is required for most interviews, and some things - like the murals on the oldest church in Eatonville, painted by a white man, showing black men in the fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a fat teacher with a soft spot for bright red, still fear that their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet, as Hurston Festival expanded, a high level of civic pride also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston seeing his entire race: beautiful, troubled and all, neither better nor worse and proud, creative, hardworking, silly and confused like other races and ethnic groups in America.
It is genuine civic affection that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for the local government or the police department, who he said might need help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Many people, if they just came in here, will think, 'Oh, this town is nothing compared to all the others,'" said Alondra Kenon after the Mass on a recent Sunday.
"But if you really stop and take a moment to look at the history, it's a really nice city".
Here in New York we all speak fluently about finance
On the surface, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newspaper stands and the huge TV screens in Times Square, they would not realize they were in the eye of the cyclone.
They would never guess that the glass offices, the beehives overhead the bankers and hedge fund managers who monopolize New York City are having their worst day at the office every day since the crash of 1929.
Mailmen shake metal tea carts across the sidewalks, carrying muffin trays for breakfast meetings.
Latin Americans drag their feet between condominiums carrying, like human mules, 50 broken stretched shirts hanging from a stick on their shoulders.
Employees still wait in line for their morning bagels at the food carts on the sidewalks, and it is still impossible to catch a yellow taxi between 4 and 7 p.m. on a workday.
It didn't seem like there was a real crisis, until, with all the talk of ruin and sadness, I decided to open a new savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Although I had planned the event to coincide with my late afternoon break at my JP Morgan Chase branch, a line of about twenty was already waiting in line.
Not in front of the cash register, to withdraw money or make deposits, but in front of the customer service desk, where old customers order checkbooks, tourists ask directions to the Macy's department store, and new customers open accounts.
Many of those in front of me, I would later learn from Starr, my "trusted banker", were in line for the same reason I was.
Unlike me, however, they've already taken their savings from smaller banks from places they commute from, like New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They have taken money from so-called thrift (sort of like a construction company), credit unions and kind of citizen savings banks whose branches only operate within a state, and they say they treat customers like family members.
In the past few years, 15 of these banks have gone bankrupt.
In recent days Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, was placed under a management buy-out, and as New Yorkers headed home for the weekend on a Friday afternoon, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in savings deposits, was looking for a buyer to bail it out.
The employees and the contractors standing in front of me, afraid of another collapse, were moving their money to a bank perceived as a safe haven, the bank that is asking for the most bail-outs on Wall Street.
The average New Yorker has become a financial expert in the last few weeks.
A woman at my trusted Chinese supermarket, speaking on the phone, referred to Lehman Brothers, the failed bank, and its emaciated CEO Dick Fuld in a familiar way, as if complaining about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed, almost 50-year-old janitor at my condo, changed the subject from our usual conversation about Brad and Angelina or the delivery of my groceries.
She told me, after my visit to the bank, "Now I have all my savings in market funds!
I'm not taking any chances".
Muslim graves desecrated as Austria turns right.
Heinz-Christian Strache, left of the Austrian right wing of the Freedom Party, and Filip Dewinter of the Belgian right-wing Vlaams Belang party, take part in a demonstration to present the organization "City against Islamization" in Antwerp, Thursday, January 17, 2008.
They carry signs like those street signs representing mosques with a red line running through them.
Police blamed right-wing extremists for desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria, the same week that far-right political parties won big in the national general election.
More than 90 graves were severely damaged at Traun Cemetery near Linz in a few hours between Friday night and this morning in what police believe was an organized action.
The perpetrators sprayed Jewish symbols like the Star of David over some graves, but detectives believe it may have been an attempt to mask extremist motives driven by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It's unclear if the incident is election related.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" by the news of the desecration, which took place towards the end of Ramadan, a month of religious significance for Muslims.
Austria, meanwhile, has embarked on a spiritual journey following its rightward turn in yesterday's parliamentary elections.
The two far-right parties that won almost 30 percent of the vote, the Austrian Freedom Party and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, campaigned with strong anti-immigration bills and some of their slogans have been described by xenophobic critics.
Heinz-Christian Strache, the leader of the Freedom Party who won more than 18 percent of the vote, has campaigned against veils and burkas and has also expressed his opposition to foods that are perceived to be connected to Islam.
At the final rally in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the growth of Islam.
Both parties seem to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, citing them as political symbols of the continuing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses made immediately after the elections, which established the far right as the strongest political bloc in the nation, indicated that the change was driven predominantly by young voters who are concerned about their future in the European Union.
Foreign travel banned for Gary Glitter.
Gary Glitter, the glamorous rock star guilty of child sexual abuse, has been banned from traveling to France and Spain by the court.
Magistrates imposed a six-month ban on Glitter after he informed the authorities who monitored him that he wanted to go to Spain via France.
The travel ban was granted to Kent police last Thursday after they provided the magistrates with proof of Glitter's previous arrests for child sexual abuse.
Glitter, real name Paul Gadi, was not present at the Ashford Prosecution in Kent but was represented by Corker Binning's lawyers.
A Court Service spokesman said: "On Thursday 25 September at Ashford Precinct, Kent Police filed a request to prevent Mr Paul Gadd's overseas travel to France and Spain until 25 March.
"Paul Gadd was not present in person".
Glitter, 64, had informed authorities that he wanted to travel abroad as required by the sex offender registry.
He must notify the authorities if he wishes to travel abroad for more than three days.
He is also required to give the police seven days' notice of his intended departure date.
Failure to notify the authorities can lead to a five-year prison sentence.
Kent P.D. said they don't want to discuss individual cases or Glitter's possible movements around the country.
A Kent Police spokesman said: "Kent Police will do whatever is necessary to protect children in this country or abroad.
"From our point of view, it is easier to monitor someone staying in the UK because we have the right comprehensive systems to manage any potential risk more effectively.
"Protecting Kent residents is Kent Police's top concern and we work closely to monitor the behaviour of convicted sex offenders registered in the country to minimise any potential risk to the public.
Glitter returned to the UK last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for molesting two girls aged 10 and 11.
When Glitter came, he flew to Bangkok where he was supposed to board a flight to London.
But he said he felt sick and refused to fly to London.
The Thai authorities wouldn't let him go through passport control and he ended up on a flight to Hong Kong.
Even the Chinese authorities did not let him in and he returned to Bangkok where the Thai police and immigration officials insisted that he return to England.
He finally arrived at Heathrow Terminal 3 on 22 August and stayed there while his lawyer David Corker went to Uxbridge Prosecutor's Office, west of London, as Scotland Yard had successfully applied for an order to register him for sex offenders.
Glitter had previously been jailed in the UK in 1999 for possessing child abuse images.
A source at the Home Office said Jacqui Smith, the Home Secretary, was reassured and happy that Glitter had been stopped from traveling to France and Spain.
"I photograph the master away from the scene to extract the character" Günther Bauer, photographer
No heels or flyers or old clothes.
Just the essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of the concentration that characterizes the performance, to look at the relaxed appearance of the man or woman.
On one side is the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Two faces inseparable, except in private, in those moments away from the public, when the intimacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of the hands, are natural because they don't have to go on stage.
German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco-People" alternates the theatricality of some shots of singers, dancers and guitarists on stage with the lesser known side of these masters.
With this objective, the photographer offers an original iconography of flamenco, capturing it from different angles.
The exhibition, included in the programming of the Flamenco Photography Month, reflects the international importance of this dance, which is growing every day", explains the artist and clarifies that in "Flamenco-People" it could also be about ordinary people, but by looking at the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists, performers or performers on the scene.
These "on the street" people are "artists who can convey passion, sadness, joy when they are on stage ... and capture the audience.
To capture the personality of these great men, you don't have to portray them on stage.
Because their personality and character are internal.
What I was interested in was creating an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture with my camera the personalities of the great flamenco artists".
With his passion for the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to portray singers, guitarists or dancers using a plate camera.
These are portraits that, because of the type of machine and the material, resemble classic photography.
The application of different stylistic techniques breaks with the traditional principles of the image, giving the photo modernity, according to an idea that reflects Bauer's own conception of flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and is able to surprise every day".
Not the dancing, the singing, the playing itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, his ability to win over the audience with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential elements, with the magic that becomes visible in a certain way of feeling and being, are and have been the constant of this work, on display these days at the gallery El Fotómata.
Famous flamenco artists such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are featured in this selection of about seventy portrait artists.
The project has become a kind of anthology of flamenco, and will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited at the exhibition.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with "SportARTproject".
Although the concept is different in "Flamenco-People", the photographer admits, "I love to portray people, to get to know them and to be able to penetrate for a moment in their life, whether that moment is long or short.
I think portraiture is the hardest genre in photography.
You meet or confront people, characters you sometimes don't even know or who give you just a few minutes to take the picture.
Beyond these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true".
The collection of contemporary flamenco portraits, entitled "Flamenco-people", is set up at the El Fotómata gallery, at number 20 of Via de la Mata, parallel to Via Alameda de Hercules, and will be open to the public until 16 October.
Vargas Llosa reveals that the novel he is writing is a "chance"
It is set in places he does not yet know and deals with unknown topics: despite this, Mario Vargas Llosa is struggling with a new project he is working on, a novel whose protagonist, Roger Casemant, is an Irish nationalist who has lived for twenty years in Congo and has crossed the Amazon.
The writer, who has always been a favorite for the Nobel Prize in Literature, confessed yesterday at the Hay Festival in Segovia that the project he is working on today "is a gamble" and that "everything indicates that I should not write it".
"If I had good sense, I wouldn't write it, but I'll do it anyway and I hope to finish it as soon as possible", he concluded his speech at the festival for the exchange of ideas, thoughts and words that for four days saw a hundred writers, historians, journalists and thousands of people pass through the city of Aquedotto.
The author of "La ciudad y los perros" was, as predicted, the leading figure at the third edition of the festival of the word.
Vargas Llosa, who won the Hay Festival prize for being the most voted writer by the participants  an old edition of Dickens' book "Our mutual friend", filled the seats of the Juan Bravo theatre.
Presented by Félix Romeo, the writer found himself in front of a public to whom time flew when the Peruvian, with a prodigious memory and with great doses of humor, recalled how the literary vocation was born in him, derived from the "extraordinary adventure" of the "pleasure of reading" and "of living beyond what I lived"; how he writes in a "disciplined way" to compensate for the "lack of inspiration", with an intense work of documentation, editing and continuous re-making; how Faulkner, Victor Hugo and Alexandre Dumas have influenced his vocation and how "the images of memory" are the basis on which his stories rest.
The Spanish-American novelist, recognized that "there is no way" to measure and know if books can change people's lives, "but I refuse to believe that literature is a pure entertainment, an ephemeral experience", Vargas Llosa stressed, arguing that, on the contrary, "it has effects" and that "it makes people more anticonformist". For this he invited writers to "not give in to frivolity" and to "assume responsibility" for their vocation.
The weather is hindering the Pozoblanco Festival, depriving it of the rides
