"Sangre de mayo", the epic wager of Garci
Inspired by Episodios Nacionales by Benito Pérez Galdós, Jose Luis Garci reproposes in Sangre de mayo the famous revolt of the Spaniards against the French, in what is the most ambitious film of his filmography, with almost 15 million euros budget.
With this film, the director has tried to "illustrate the torrent of characters and at the same time the social analysis" that he has always admired in the work of the famous novelist, he explained today during the presentation of the film, with Quim Gutierrez and Paula Echevarría at the head of a large cast of performers.
Sangre de mayo, which runs for more than two and a half hours, debuts in cinemas this Friday, and will become a four-hour television miniseries on TeleMadrid.
A great admirer of Galdós's literature, Jose Luis Garci claims that he has realized with this film "a dream of his childhood", and believes he must thank Esperanza Aguirre, who had commissioned him from the Community of Madrid three years before filming a commemorative film for the second centenary of May 2nd.
The 15 million budget allocated entirely by the Community of Madrid represented for Garci a 'unique opportunity' to recreate the appropriate sets and costumes to portray a 'stunned Spain that made a mistake in choosing the leader to fight for and the fact that the struggle for independence brought the people a huge backlog in development under the reign of Ferdinand VII', Garci noted.
However, the director regrets not having received funding equal to those of Alatriste or Los fantasmas de Goya - more than double that of Sangre de mayo, so it was not possible to shoot some scenes provided by the scenography that he himself had signed together with Horacio Valcarcel, a collaborator of almost all his career.
This, for the director of Volver a empezar, has influenced what is his usual work practice, the staging with the actors, with whom he often rehearses before shooting together with those who will not be part of the cast, because he considers it "humiliating", considering that "part of the director's work lies in going to the theater and the cinema to know what is happening in the sector in which he works".
Many of the performers, some of whom are part of the cast of Sangre de mayo, rehearse in front of his car, as in the case of Michael Rell, Carlos Larranaga or Fernando Guillen Cuervo.
Four times Oscar nominee - winning one - Garci believes that none of the three films nominated to represent Spain at the Hollywood Academy this year - his Sangre de mayo, Siete mesas de billar francés and, the last selected Los girasoles ciegos -, represent the younger generation of Spanish cinema "which should be known".
This Garci movie doesn't expect awards.
"At first you think you're working for posterity, then you realize you're only working for prosperity, and at some point you just settle for making one more film", explains Garci after more than 30 years in the business.
Isabel Bayon rediscovers the Sicilian essence of the dancer Tortola Valencia
A Sicilian dancer pays tribute to another dancer from Seville.
Carmen Valencia Tortola, Catalan father (Firenze Tortola Ferrer) and Andalusian mother (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the Triana district, and at the age of three moved with her family to London.
She was a freestyle dancer and a specialist in oriental dances.
She led a fascinating life and was a pioneer of women's emancipation, the likes of Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and a vegetarian, and she advocated for the abolition of the corset that prevented women from moving freely.
The life of this woman, who marked a revolution in dance and aesthetics in Europe between the two world wars, has always fascinated Isabel Bayon.
"I would have loved to work with Pepa Gamboa and she offered me this character.
She says: "We don't want to tell her whole life, but to collect her spirit.
The titles of his dances suggested to me some basic elements of flamenco.
So, "the butterfly dance" suggested a guajira, or "the snake dance" some tangis.
Her dance was sensual and I was told that my own dance also fits into this aesthetic", she explains.
The staging includes two exceptional contributions: that of Miguel Poveda, who will sing Isabel again in one of his shows, as he does in "La puerta abierta"; and that of the teacher Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to work with her who had been a student.
"Matilde plays Tortola as an adult, the character of maturity.
I am happy that he has agreed to work on my work, and I am very honored".
The set also includes the musical composition and guitarists such as Jesus Torres and Paco Arriaga, the singing of Miguel Ortega, the Pulga y Moi by Morón; the percussions of El Pájaro, as well as the viola by Rafa La Viola and the collaboration of an actor, Juanfran Juárez "who plays the role of eternal companion of these artists who have been all-round divas, and who have always had many fans".
The work also includes some form of the life of this woman, which takes place in distant places, especially for that time, such as India, the United States or Russia, and then all over Europe, since she usually lived in London.
"I wanted to remember her because I think she is one of the women who had a huge impact in a given historical period and now nobody remembers her, much less considers her work as something of value", says Bayon.
The show will start today at 8:30 p.m. at the Lope de Vega Theater.
