Recurrent alcoholic drivers will have to install the "alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior requires drivers with three administrative penalties for excessive blood alcohol levels to install in their car the system that prevents the driving of the vehicle in a state of drunkenness or if you do not blow in the appropriate device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the State Prosecutor's Office, which says it will be a pilot project lasting one year.
The aim of this project is to reintegrate the driver, who will have to undergo a rehabilitation course on the road.
In addition to the Public Prosecutor's Office for Road Safety, the Directorate-General for Traffic (DGT) and the Technological Institute for Automobile Safety (FITSA) Foundation will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 percent of those who are reported to have drunk driven more than once then drive again.
The alcohol lock would avoid this, because it is a system attached to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not blow, or when a higher concentration of alcohol is detected than is permitted.
The cost is over 1000 euros and would be borne by the offender.
In this respect, a study carried out in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles fitted with such devices reduce infringements by up to 65% during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain, it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to curb such behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And to facilitate its development, since legal reform can be carried out in the ordinary way, and, no doubt, the reform necessary for criminal procedure would require an organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been introduced experimentally in some industrial and public vehicles.
Tomorrow the Congress of Deputies will vote on a PSOE initiative to install this system in school buses, as has already been done in France.
