Talking in your sleep
Some children talk at night.
I don't mean those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but those babies who talk while they're asleep.
The first time it happens, you're scared at best, but it doesn't really matter.
It's a benign alteration of sleep called somnolence.
It occurs with some frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely most of you have been told that you talked in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in a lifetime, for example associated with an episode of high fever) or more regularly (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the next day the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason that can explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes these episodes are linked to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, bedwetting, or sleepwalking, but not necessarily.
As mentioned earlier, it may be associated with stages of very high fever, stress or overexcitation.
However, it is still a phenomenon that has been little studied.
The intensity of its appearance is also extremely variable.
It may be that the person speaks in a very calm tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper, or the opposite may occur (crying, shouting, long speeches, etc.).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be wise to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to see if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outlet for the situation.
We have said that it is a benign alteration so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stressful situation).
What you can do, however, is to consider a number of very simple preventive measures, such as:
Try not to over-excite the baby before he goes to bed.
Suggest calm games and avoid TV shows or programs that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children who find it difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain a measure of inner calm.
This will allow the baby to sleep more comfortably.
Once the sleepwalkers appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what happened.
Helpful Tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless, because he's not aware of what's going on, and you'd interrupt his sleep.
Although he is talking, he is sleeping and therefore resting.
Remember, if the child seems very anxious and the episodes are frequent, it is best to consult a doctor or to find out what is causing such anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not the most common situation), do not be tempted to question him for information.
You'll get nothing, because he's asleep and therefore unconscious to organize his thought.
In addition, you can hear what he says but not see what he is dreaming about saying, so you need to be very careful about interpreting the information and the conclusions it might lead to.
Never tell the child that you may ask questions at night to learn his secrets.
Not for fun.
Something like that causes a tremendous amount of distress.
In short, don't worry, it's nothing serious, it's an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
