The Meeting - Blood Is Safe Again
Héma-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And most importantly, he regained the public's trust, which had been shaken by the blood-infected scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood supply run by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service was infected by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a tragedy and public protests, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994 under the direction of Justice Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent a recurrence of a similar disaster.
While Judge Krever was delayed in drafting a report, some provinces set up a committee with the goal of devising a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec for the supply of Quebec and Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its operations, only 38% of people said they still had confidence in the Quebec donation system, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Through continuous efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and field research over the years, we have regained the public's trust", she explains, before proudly stating that by early 2008, about 94% of the population of Quebec now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow in Europe, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the woman who has been chairman of the Commission since 1998, the year of its founding.
"And we had no idea that the disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
We have therefore taken one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, namely that when there is doubt and a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, may result, exclusion measures should be taken.
In April 1999, blood was refused from those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
Now, for some years, it has been shown beyond a doubt that this disease is transmitted through infected blood.
This incident has shown us that the precautionary principle made sense".
In 1999 a much more efficient technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (NATs), which detect the presence of the virus directly in the blood of donors rather than antibodies to it, on which previous tests were based.
The NATs have shortened the window period, from when a person contracted the disease to when the first viruses can be detected in the blood with our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and thus failing to identify them has thus been greatly reduced.
These improvements have greatly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood samples will need to be distributed before anyone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples each year, it will be more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted by transfusion is detected.
I believe that today one can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to restore health, says the head of the Héma-Québec administration.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
You never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not more than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island. Like the West Nile virus, it is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
We must be constantly vigilant", continues Dr. Décary, before pointing out that in addition to having secure resources, Héma-Québec must also ensure that it provides enough.
"Needs are increasing as the population ages.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the number of donors, who on average make up only 3% of Quebecers eligible as donors".
However, all healthy persons over 18 years of age who meet the eligibility criteria may donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who volunteer as donors are not accepted, because if they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is widespread, they will be rejected for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we are able to maintain an inventory capable of meeting the needs of hospitals.
The shortage is very rare.
But the members of this group of donors need to be renewed as they get older and can no longer donate.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but more importantly to keep them and to encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that it is hard to find an hour to donate blood", lamented Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissue, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited at Héma-Québec, which runs the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
Once considered biomedical waste, the umbilical cord is rich in stem cell-rich blood that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated the deposit of our thousandth cord blood sample a few weeks ago and plan to draw more than a thousand each year.
They should be available for transplantation early next year", says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of cord blood as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot have access to it", as Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
