The Northern Plan is the fourth item in a 'project' which the Prime Minister claims to have for Quebec, that of a 'new economic area', which includes a first agreement with France on labour, a second agreement between Canada and Europe and other agreements with Ontario.
Often mentioned in the Prime Minister's most recent speeches, the opening of the North - the territory north of the 49th parallel - had never been the subject of a presentation.
The Prime Minister, however, confined himself to explaining why the North would be "a jewel with immense potential", but did not comment on timing or investment quotas, nor did he explain what the precise priorities would be in the implementation of future projects.
He has at most limited himself to what he considers to be a priority: hydroelectricity, forestry, but above all the mining sector, which has seen several improvements as a result of the growth of the emerging countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructure.
According to Charest's list, the North contains "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and even diamonds".
That "territory twice the size of France" is here, in Quebec.
It is not only here, but it is in us", he insisted, as if to call out a national founding myth.
The foundations of Quebec are rooted in its relationship with the North, he stressed: the gold rush in Abitibi, national engineering, James Bay.
"It's up to us, it's our future", he added, after a dramatic pause to contemplate the huge map behind him.
The north, 70% of Quebec's territory, includes a part of Labrador which Quebec has always claimed, the Prime Minister said during the press conference.
It is a position traditionally held by all governments.
There is a border line on which no agreement has been reached for a long time and when the opportunity arises I will reiterate that position on behalf of the government", he said.
Moreover, "considering climate change, we need to re-evaluate the North", he said, referring to the North-West Passage, which will be open all year round because of the melting of the ice.
In this new geopolitical context, the Prime Minister considers it a duty to occupy the territory.
What about the First Nations and the Inuit?
The Prime Minister said that the Quebec government would be very careful about this and that the project would be in their interests, especially those of young people.
Two former ministers from different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (former PQ member from Ungva), have already launched a consultation of some 30 communities.
