Letters - A country disgraced
It was Vic Toews, former Justice Minister in the Harper cabinet, who dared to declare last summer that Louise Arbor was a "disgrace" to Canada.
To disgrace in this way a woman who has fought tirelessly for justice and who deserves all our admiration says a lot about both the Prime Minister's entourage and Stephen Harper himself.
We are faced with a government which is the only one of all the Western countries involved which has not repatriated a citizen detained in the Guantanamo concentration camp.
A government that takes no account of the fact that Omar Khadr was a mere teenager at the time of the events he is accused of.
The only government that, despite signing the Geneva Convention, has reneged on its word and let a child soldier rot in inhumane conditions.
The only one who relies on a travesty of justice to establish the guilt of the accused.
For your information, UNICEF, Amnesty International and the Canadian Bar Association in particular are calling for Omar Khadra to be returned to Canada so that he can be tried in a fair trial.
It is the very government that turns a blind eye to torture: it gives little thought to the fact that a young adult is now psychologically destroyed, perhaps forever, after so many years of suffering.
