Free speech - The Orwellian speech by Barrick Gold
In the September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from M. Patrick J. Garver, vice-president and managing director of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has filed a six-million-dollar defamation suit against three authors and a small, disreputable publishing house with the intention of initiating a "transparent public debate".
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in a defamation case, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this substantial difference is completely hidden by Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to take a position contrary to his.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the writers and the publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend a considerable sum of money in order to organize their own defense and fight, with decidedly unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers financed by the practically bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, in these unfair armed conflicts, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual regulation that will silence the opposition and scare anyone who dares to speak out again on the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before the public that it should have presented its view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada debates are normally held by exchange of views and not by a trickle.
It would have been enough for society to open its books, its papers, and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and funding of independent research teams that could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have much confidence in the public and is badly rejecting petitions and letters of support from Black Canadian authors.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can call for a "public" debate when his contempt for that same public is so evident?
In the Vice President's world, it seems that this word refers exclusively to the well-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even the slanderers have a say.
What Barrack Gold doesn't understand or doesn't want to understand is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does so primarily because they reject the brutal means adopted by the mining company.
This audience is ready to listen to Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civil exchanges of opinion, and not in the light of what many perceive as a kind of muffling (looking for the "public debate", Barrick Gold just gave the authors of Black Canada an ultimatum instructing them to suspend the use of that word...)
Beyond Garver's surreal speech, the lawsuit brought by Barrack Gold is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in any democratic society.
It denies the right to quote authentic sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss topics that are uncomfortable for the richest companies in the world, or multiple lawsuits, who will do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do it by following the scientific norms as the authors of Black Canada do.
You have a right to a reply.
The university environment, of which we are a part, has long been capable of handling debate and disagreement and of resolving conflict.
Barrick Gold's excessive measures clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it does not seek a transparent debate at all.
This is to the detriment of the academic community, as is the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to take measures to limit abusive litigation.
