Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
The blue-eyed beauty was for a long time his ace in the hole, for others his weak spot.
Did he get rid of the narcissistic mirror, the American actor with the charming smile?
Yes and no.
His discretion, sensitivity and obvious talent would have banished him from that circle of powerful ones devoted to real sacred monsters.
What a consistency!
Paul Newman, who died Friday at the age of 83 at his Connecticut ranch from lung cancer, remains one of the last iconic American film stars of the silent era.
Less monumental than Brando, who he resembled and who for a long time was a kind of rival on the screen, more cautious in his play, certainly more fragile, but also he was a spokesman for freedom and the development of dramatic convictions.
Mixed couples often have magical children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, to a German Jewish father and a Hungarian mother.
From these European roots will emerge one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
A lowly ego, the ultimate mark of quality.
Because he was a country-spanning safe-made man, a proud combat veteran of the Pacific War, who in the early 1950s studied drama at Yale, later attended the Actor Studio in New York, before triumphing in theater, television and soon in film.
That same civil rights activist was also the car driver who placed second in the 1979 24 Hours of Le Mans, as well as a sex symbol, though part of a model pair since 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
With him goes the shadowy areas of a secretive, discreet, busy star, allergic to the scandals of show business, whose mystery will never be fully unraveled.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the word.
This weekend, the passing of Paul Newman has been a heartbreaking moment for film fans, as his great characters populate the black screen of memories.
Over half a century of American cinema in full transformation is reproposed through his interpretations.
They confuse the memory of Butch Cassidy's charming cowboy and that boy unable to desire his fiery wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on the Burning Roof adapted by Tennessee Williams in 1958.
More recently, we remember him as the sensitive Mr. Bridge (1990), troubled by a marriage that didn't deliver on its promises.
Many other Paul Newmans have passed down through history.
The boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Someone Loves Me, by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean and resumed after his death, which officially launched Newman in 1956.
That cute villain in the excellent Stangata, Oscar for best picture in 1973.
A bitter and vindictive billiards player in Robert Rossen's magnificent film The Spaghetti Man (1961), Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which earned him the only Oscar out of 9 nominations in 1987.
That face over the years, it was his.
He's here again.
The ages follow through on its path.
Young people know him best for the cult movie Slap Shot- Dry Shot by George Roy Hill (1977), as Reggie Dunlop, coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in Mr. Hula Hoop, by the Coen brothers.
The circle was closed with one last Irish mob godfather role in It Was My Father, in 2003.
Unlike the more established film legends who left the business early, Newman will remain in theaters for a long time, denouncing Hollywood in all its glitz, parties and concessions.
Bertrand Tavernier, a French film-loving man, described it, with a touch of irony, as "a living challenge to underplaying", judging its performances as exaggerated.
The profession wasn't always a game for the handsome Paul Newman, to whom roles seemed to fall like manna from the sky.
However, he often preferred the role of the outcast to that of the young actor: neurotic, alcoholic, or desperate characters, of whom he expressed disdain and rebellion with his perfect traits.
As a director, Newman revealed unknown shades of his true, modest sensibility.
Jennifer's first time, 1968 (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), with his wife Joanne Woodward in the title role, drew a subtle female portrait of melancholy.
He, who lost his son Scott to an overdose, dedicated Harry and Son to him in 1984, a discreet and sad film.
Among the countless tributes poured down on Newman yesterday, his great friend and old comrade-in-arms Robert Redford (they had starred together in The Stangata and Butch Cassidy) said with endless sadness, "His presence has made my life and this country better".
Generosity and love of life, two great characteristics of the late actor.
Beyond a career as a legend, he's a great civil rights activist, environmentalist, independent filmmaker, a challenger to the Hollywood drift.
We'll have seen his face stand out on vinegar bottles, sauces, cookies and other foods, judging it a choice of bad taste, though born as a gag.
The proceeds from those sales, however, went to his Foundation for Children in Need.
Newman, instead of leaning on his myth, chose to commit to the end.
He left his five daughters a letter that said, "Always and to the end, your father was incredibly grateful to his good star.
It was a privilege to be there".
And it was just as privileged for us to follow the path of such a clear and generous American artist.
Model citizen, then, and much more.
What was produced in the Zuschlag & Associates factories?
Soon, on October 8, the hearing of the criminal trial against János Zuschlag and associates will be discussed.
The politician and his associates are accused of repeated commercial fraud committed within a criminal association that caused considerable damage, and of other crimes, including forgery of documents.
According to the prosecution, the money obtained from tendering was used by them for private purposes, and they often certified the performance of the activities by means of false invoices.
The state and municipal money, totalling 65 million florins, has partly ended up in the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal organization, partly in the pockets of some people.
According to the method, as made known by the investigating authorities, they have drawn the money obtained from competitive tenders on the basis of invoices for transactions which do not exist and the associations have never fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the invoices were false.
The invoice blocks were purchased at the Józsefváros market, while the circular stamps were manufactured in Kiskunhalas.
And to decide on behalf of which companies to issue invoices, it was established among other things during the hill trip over the Balaton where János Zuschlag had sent István Lados.
According to the latter's confession, he had to choose between boarding houses and restaurants.
The Commission has requested invoices for consumption, and invoices have been prepared for the tendering procedures, among others, for the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs and the Budapest Municipality.
Most of these are the work of István Lados and András Őri, who, according to our information, wrote the reports necessary to obtain the funds.
One of the choices of the "studios trip" of Lados was a brewery.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and associates in 2003, the restaurant served meals to a group of 90 people from Biztos Pont Egyesület.
But so many people, according to the restaurateur, would not all enter the restaurant at once.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later renamed Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, is full of formal and content errors.
A guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj has only three rooms, more than 10 people could not stay overnight, however the bill included 130 guests.
But the compilers of the fancy invoices were exaggerating when they reported Pigal Kft., also a catering company, whose accounts - according to the information provided to the judicial authorities - did not even contain documents in the name of the companies Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, the company's manager, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor's office and shown the invoices, he immediately realized that they were false documents.
"The stamp had the name and VAT number of our company in the wrong place".
He added: "Besides the formal reasons, it was not even possible to accept the fact that according to the bill, 100 people were accommodated, when in total they have 11 rooms and there are not so many beds.
The bill was for catering, and their restaurant has been out of business for a while.
The constant invoicing staff did not bother to find out that the Budapest travel agency of their choice only arranges trips abroad, so they foolishly pointed out on the invoice that cash-paid trips to Hungary were not in line with the company's invoicing practice.
In addition, as demonstrated during the investigation, the invoice also contained VAT, while the travel activity to countries outside the European Union is VAT-free.
Moreover, the amount of VAT was also incorrect on the four documents issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. in favour of the Jobb Jövőért foundation, since the VAT on the services offered by the company was 15% and not 25% as indicated on the invoices, and the hotel employees only issued printed invoices, whereas the manufactured invoice was handwritten.
In addition, the 'issuers' ruined other invoices, in the case of a company they indicated as carried out the transport of goods by road, as it is known from the prosecution's proceedings, an activity which was not carried out by the company originally founded for investment advice.
Furthermore, due to formal defects - the case was filed in the form of a non-conforming invoice, false stamp - it was found that the invoices issued in favour of Együtt at Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont were false.
The same was true of Ravenna Bt. or Kunfehértó Sports Ground, whose representatives denied having issued the invoices in question.
The counterfeiters did not even pay attention to the fact that HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in liquidation when (2001) a group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület lunched there, which is why the curator of the liquidation of the company, according to our information, denied that he issued that invoice.
They've been billing people knowingly.
Another group of invoice issuers are those who were aware that they had to issue fake invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány foundation has issued an invoice at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták for the Együtt foundation in Harmadik Évezredért of almost 4 million florins.
Ludovic Györfi, one of the defendants, according to the indictment, persuaded the director of Collab Kft. to issue fake invoices.
Together with Zuschlag and partners, Biogate Kft, currently in liquidation, also collaborated, providing invoices worth around HUF 5 million to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület association in 2003, which did not have any real economic activity behind them.
No movement of money because the prepared invoices were then returned, but the associations forgot to make this point in their documents.
The following group of invoicing firms are those that are linked to the defendants.
For example, Ivan Kubatov, authorised to the address of the Managing Director of Delta Trió Kft, based in Budapest but not available there, which deals in fuel and motor vehicles.
The company issued various invoices in October, November and December 2005 for the sale of IT equipment, worth approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which has been in liquidation since 14 September 2005, purchased these invoices.
The CEO of this company was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov allegedly forwarded the documents concerning the company between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov, during the investigation, admitted to issuing invoices on behalf of the company to the companies Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt at Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány and the countervalue was collected from him.
At the express request of Ivan Kubatov, Romanian masons founded the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In fact, none of the firms were in operation, because the defendant claimed that they had not been employed.
The companies were nevertheless useful to him because, at the request of the co-defendant lawyer Zsolt Szente, draftsman of the company's articles of association, invoices were issued on behalf of the companies to the associations linked to Zuschlag: Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
On behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, Kubatov issued 15 invoices to the various entities for a total value of HUF 14,2 million.
Prosecutors believe Kubatov pocketed 10% of the invoice amounts, plus the VAT.
The man also used the Szi-Beri Bt. to issue fake invoices, manufactured for Biztos Pont's call for competition.
Y-Generáció and Szövetség at Modern Magyarországért in January 2006 submitted a tender for the public utility body of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They also won 500,000 florins each but the sums were not used for the purposes indicated in the tender.
To prevent this from coming to light, they submitted to TMA five fake invoices received by Works Team Kft.
These bills were found during a search of Árpád Kemecsei's office at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, as the prosecutor has already done, some of the defendants will probably report on the progress of the invoice production.
However, the most interesting thing could be if the defendant number one, János Zuschlag, decides to lift the veil on everything.
His confession so far has not been very detailed and although he has promised several times to talk about everything in a comprehensive way, he has not done so yet.
It is to be seen whether it is in his interest, it may also be that the Socialists have made agreements with Zusi, who - in return for compensation of 50 million florins, a large part of the damage - would be willing to be the scapegoat.
Mr Zuschlag could also have been offended at the moment, since his requests for relief from his prison conditions, i.e. the granting of house arrest, have not been met.
The Commission has not yet decided whether to grant the aid to the victims of the terrorist attacks.
The psychology of over-bidding: Why spend more money?
At auctions, buyers are likely to spend more, to overvalue the goods.
Researchers, neuroscientists and economists at New York University, have been able to discover the neuro-economic basis of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
Their study, published in the journal Science, found that men do not want to fall behind in a competition such as the eBay auction, so they are willing to pay even higher prices.
The research has tried to trace the neural pattern of this "match" at the nervous system level by experimental tricks.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other group of players participated in an auction, and they used functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) to examine the active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment.
In both games, the participants could win money, but in the auction game, where the essential element is to bid more than the other, the striated body under the cerebral cortex comes into intense action when you lose the game.
This brain area, along with other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
So the researchers say the price increase is explained by the striated body's fierce reaction to the scanning.
To support their theory, the economists in the research group carried out a financial tracking survey.
In this survey three groups bid against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the actual value of the product concerned and they made their bet.
Another group was promised another $15 prize if they won.
The third group would receive $15 before the auction, but the members of the group would lose money if they lost the auction.
The difference between the two groups was that one group was highlighted as winning, while the other group was highlighted as losing.
Testing the neurologists' hypothesis, members of the "lose" group were willing to bet higher than the control or "win" group.
"These results are not deductible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
The Commission has also been able to provide a number of proposals for the future of the European Union.
Only the methods of creating the neurological image have helped to resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so that we have come to a third explanation", said Andrew Schotter, professor at the New York University School of Economics.
Hepatitis - When to See a Doctor?
Nearly half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and chronic liver disease is among the leading causes of death in Hungary.
In Hungary, the number of hepatitis patients is 100,000, of whom only 7,000 are treated, because many do not know they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name for infectious liver diseases caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical being hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases they cause differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the food chain (e.g. infected water and food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal discharge, saliva).
It is useful for travellers to be vaccinated against A and B viruses, there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated food, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain, and nausea.
After that, yellow spots form on the skin and the white of the eyes, stools become clear and urine dark, and healing occurs within two to three weeks.
A million people die each year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason is that it is estimated that only one in ten people receive treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: If left untreated, it can cause cirrhosis of the liver and liver tumors.
Most infected people do not know they have the disease because the pathogens subtly destroy liver cells, and in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20 to 30 years.
So it is very important to prevent and to carry out regular medical tests.
This disease is much more common than average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
Worldwide, the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus now stands at 200 million.
Since even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease, it is worthwhile to consult your family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
If the disease is recognized early, it is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, thus stopping the infectious power and preventing the formation of tumors.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first celebrated in 2004 by disease associations around the world.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and the early detection of the disease.
Do people who believe in God feel less pain?
According to a recent survey, religious faith acts as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment, examining how belief in God affects the feeling of pain, reports Britain's Telegraph.
In the rather bizarre survey, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were electrocuted while all were observing a painting of the Virgin Mary.
The results showed that Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
By exploring the human brain, it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
The test is the first in a series of research projects involving not only academics but also scientists, philosophers and theologians from the University.
The test went exactly like this: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was attached to the left hand of the subject.
The researchers asked the participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with the Cinderella painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary would create a kind of religious state among believers, while Leonardo's painting was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and they considered it to have a calming effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive sets, while they were either observing the religious painting or the other.
Catholics reported that the vision of the virgin Mary made them feel "secure", as if "someone was taking care" of them and "they were reassured and filled with peace".
When they looked at the religious image, they reported 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo's work in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that a similar result can be achieved with any image that has a strong effect even on atheists, but the right image must be found.
"We need to look for an image that they feel very positive about, like a mother or a father", the psychologist said.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright was pleased with the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it does change our personality", Wright added.
After the excellent results, the only question remains: If the faithful are presented with a painting of a Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of a similar caliber, what effect might it have on pain control?
Would a vision of a quality virgin Mary bring better results?
You are what you say you are
On the day of a person's tenth birthday, Google can claim to be as much in their pockets as in the sky above their heads; it knows where they spent their holidays, what clinic they attend, and what interests them.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the firm's directors, this is not enough.
As for the skeptics who compare it to the Orwellian nightmare, they don't really see the substance of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main goal is to collect as much personal data as possible from its users and this is necessary to stick to the original goal of the founders of Google which was: "let's put all the information in the world into one system!".
According to the Google CEO interviewed by the company, after 10 years of revolutionary work, it is still at the beginning of being able to manage all the information.
When asked what will happen in five years, Schmidt said he would like Google to know the answers to questions like "what do I do tomorrow?" or "what would be the right job for me?" But software can't answer seemingly simple questions because it doesn't know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that when they search the Internet, the exact words they search for, the IP address from which they search and the page they stop at after searching are recorded.
The Personalized Search, which was launched two years ago, allows users to store their browsing history, to look at what they have searched for and clicked on, which will in the long run lead to much better results; the same logic is used for Recommendations, where the system offers us products and services based on our previously declared and recorded preferences.
What if my data is used against me, if they look at what I do? - ask users concerned about Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, the reactions of the netizens are caused by the fear of the size of the potential power represented by the company, and not by guilt, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or even rebellion against the power.
One fact is confirmed, however, namely that all the expressions sought are not only recorded but in justified cases can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
Perhaps the most striking example of this in recent times has been the coordinated action against pedophiles in Brazil, in which Google passed on to the Brazilian government the information that made it possible to identify pedophiles from the Orkut community page maintained by Google.
Internet users concerned about personal rights sighed with relief in May when the firm - in agreement with the EFF e-law protection association - successfully proved the truth in court against the FBI: even then you cannot force Google by any point of the constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully ripped up nearly 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms obtained in reference to the confirmation of the child protection law passed years earlier, but still failed to get the individual users' search lists and the entire list of web pages and keywords dating back two months.)
Google's judgment is therefore rather contradictory: those who are afraid to give their personal data are rushing to Google because they believe that their privacy will be affected by starting to use its services and they rise up with the rebellion of multinationals that stand out for their conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and the proliferation of computer enthusiasts, activists and users appearing in many countries see them as the next generation of big companies, the "cool corporation", as opposed to their rival, Microsoft, liquidated as the conqueror of the world because of Windows, although both are fighting for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for its services, the source code is kept up to date and the software package is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official practice of the software giant.
But it could also be because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the internet, which implies one of the most frequently repeated keywords in recent years, the Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is all about collaboration, about intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal, and while the size of these channels changes for each individual, the essence is the same: to show ourselves.
A young media person can create profiles on multiple community pages, from Facebook to Xanga, connect them to other services such as Twitter or last.fm which lists his musical tastes, all of these can be entered into systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, he can also write blogs where his latest photo galleries stored on Flickr or Picasa automatically appear.
In the meantime, we read of numerous examples where it is clear that the girl, seeing the series of photos taken in the morning from the common tour of friends, easily knows with whom her unfaithful boyfriend spent the night or a company can fire an employee because he wrote a sincere opinion about the company's top: one thing is certain, the concept of privacy has now been completely reconsidered.
People who live online make sure that they show themselves, and so we can formulate the basic thesis behind the behavior of young people.
Anyone who wants to hide something or just wants to avoid Google's monopoly can do so (starting with, for example, Scroogle using Google's search engine but at the same time voluntarily not leaving traces).
There are many people who don't sign up for community pages on purpose so they won't be found, and Google's online applications, from word processing to image management to news gathering, can be replaced by alternative versions that aren't tied to huge server parks and that don't make up our best profile yet.
The public is not so much waiting in secret for the moment when Google pulls out its claws.
At present, the company with its 156 billion dollars worth is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca Cola (110 billion dollars), AdWords/AdSense advertising spaces threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, services introduced in record time instead cause great discomfort not only to Microsoft but also to numerous software development firms.
However, critical observers find some alarming points alongside all this: the company's top management, for example, has completely rejected the protest of employees after doubling the company's nursery rate, has found the repeated daily catering to the employees' pleasure too expensive, all this however diminishes the fact that in 2006 Google bowed its head to the Chinese government and according to their agreement the company will filter all results that offend the good taste and interests of the Chinese regime.
An internal rule of the company seems to be not to advertise a new service in advance but only when it is ready to be used, but one thing is certain, that the predictable problems of the coming months and years will move the world at one point: while some believe that the project of scanning and archiving books and magazines of Google will take such proportions that the company will soon find itself in front of the US Supreme Court, others are afraid of the health system, in fact in this we can create our own health profile with our reports, medical and problems.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database may offer good material for the next generation of science fiction writers. Scroogled by the famous Cory Doctorow describes the future with Orwellian accents, where a man with Google data can be approached in alarming ways.
