The intelligent machine mimics the flight of the hornet
What better way to develop collision-prevention technology than by mimicking the obstacle sensors found in nature?
Like the ones in the bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the Calabrian engineers gave Nissan the initial strategic cue on how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic robot, a robotic mini-car with bee-like properties, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can scan all collisions.
When bees fly, they form their own oval personal space that is very similar to our protective shield - explained Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technology and research and development at the exhibition.
Important is the role of the bee's eye, which can see 300 degrees in any direction.
Engineers have tapped into the idea of the telemetric laser to replicate the function of the bee's vision.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two metres away within a 180-degree radius, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor which immediately turns it into a command to avoid a collision.
In a split second, the robot senses the obstacle and then, imitating the bee's movements, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance, unlike the present system, is entirely instinctive.
"Without this, the robot car would not be able to react quickly to avoid collisions", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the vulnerable, innermost layer of the protective shield, within which collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process has to reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees, the deviation cannot be up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steering of the wheels.
So instead of the infinite possibilities for bees to scrape other bees, the robot can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
BR23C is powered by lighter, higher energy density lithium polymer batteries, which means that their life span is longer than that of lithium ions.
Andoh believes that what is important is the instantaneity of intelligent reaction, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store it.
This robot has to process some input in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to memorize them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so it only uses a memory of a few tens of Kb.
You don't need a gigabyte or a megabyte of memory.
This is the first step towards developing an immediate collision avoidance technology which Nissan expects will be available on production vehicles within 10 years.
Further application can be provided by the integration with the GPS satellite navigation system which, by avoiding obstacles on the road, leads to the destination.
