Industrial prices continue to rise
Domestic industrial sales prices in August 2008 increased by 0,1% compared to the previous month, or 12,9% compared to August 2007 - reports the Hungarian Central Statistical Institute.
The export sales prices of the industry reported in July 2008 were higher by 1,1% compared to the previous year and decreased by 3,9%.
As a result of the change in domestic and export prices, industrial production costs were 0.7% higher than in the previous month and 3.2% higher than a year ago.
Domestic industrial sales prices increased by only 0.1% compared with the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sector also increased slightly, by 0.1%, compared with July.
The largest price increases in August 2008 were in the leather and footwear sector (2,8%), mainly in bags and belts with a 4.6% increase and in footwear production with a 2.5% monthly increase.
The high price level of plastics and chemicals has led to a significant monthly increase (1.6%) in the products and chemicals sector.
Prices fell in the oil processing sector (1.4%), in the manufacture of electrical tools and machinery (0.9%) and to a lesser extent in wood processing (0.1%)
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In the other sectors of the manufacturing industry, prices rose by between 0.2% and 0.9%.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector, prices rose by 0.3% in August in industrial domestic sales, primarily as a result of the dominant effect of the increase in the price of gas effected by the authorities since 1 July.
Compared with 12 months, taking into account domestic sales of the manufacturing industries, the largest increases were in the petroleum products processing sector (32.4%).
In the manufacture of metal products, prices rose by 13.2%, with the production of food, beverages and tobacco accounting for 11% of the increase.
Prices fell in the textile sector (2.5%) and in the manufacture of electrical tools and machinery (0.3%).
In the other manufacturing sectors, the rate of price increase varied from 0.6% to 9.1%.
In the manufacturing industry, prices rose by 10.2% in the year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector were 18.7% higher than last year.
In domestic sales among the target groups of sectors, the largest monthly price increase occurred in August in sectors producing capital goods (0.7%).
In the consumer goods sectors prices rose by 0.3%, in the energy and after-use sectors prices were unchanged compared with the previous month.
In August 2008, the largest price increase was observed in the energy and downstream sector (16.8%), compared to the same month last year.
In the sectors producing consumer goods, the increase was 6.8%, while in the investment goods sector a decrease of 1.4% was recorded.
Industrial export sales prices in guilders increased by 1.1% in August compared with the previous month, and fell by 3.9% over the same period.
