The Elites in Danger
This phenomenon was already manifested a few days ago with the House of Representatives voting against the $700 billion rescue plan launched by the White House: a significant portion of Americans were, and are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
The New York Times yesterday confirmed that the current crisis is dividing the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old, moderate East Coast soul, which is pro-federal institutions and pro-business, and its new, conservative soul, which is hostile to Washington and the financial world, especially strong in the Central and Southern states.
The soul, in fact, which has come alive by the vow I mentioned at the beginning.
This is only one example of the changes, of the great changes, which the economic earthquake is perhaps heralding or is already indicating: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not even here.
In both the United States and Europe, the crisis seems to be acting as an accelerator of long-incinerating phenomena which, in the new climate, are solidifying and finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of state-sovereignty in relation to a sort of renationalisation of the economy.
The crisis is a crisis of banking and financial institutions which, yes, have close links with the outside world, but which, above all, have the budgets of individuals and families living in one country, in one State, very much involved.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those individuals and families who, by the way, are also elected.
So the crisis appears economically global but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be largely out of the question or to have little to say: the clearest proof is the European Union, which is as usual divided between different interests and between different state strategies and fails to decide on any common policy.
And so it is from the government of each individual State that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all the allocation of funds: since when you get to the point where it is only the States that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back in order.
And they have the means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, under certain circumstances, which probably no market or international organization will ever be able to dispose of to an analogous extent.
This new emphasis on the national-statutory element, which the crisis has placed, is in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that recent developments in the economy tend to attach to a factor closely linked to that element: territoriality.
The paradox is that while we were convinced that we had entered the realm of the network, of ever more sophisticated technology, of the intangible, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future would instead have to deal increasingly with those very intangible things which are water, crops, oil.
All things that, look, can be transported from one place to another on earth but are still absolutely bound to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
So the one who happens to be the ruler of it, certainly has several more cards than the one who is not, the one who is unlucky enough to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second news, which, however, presages a fracture.
When you say Territory, State, Government, you inevitably say Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the demand for someone who can take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for the existing leadership, especially economic ones, which have proved so inadequate and full of shadowy areas.
And at the same time something even deeper and somewhat disturbing: a discredit, a discomfort, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in an increasing number of Western countries.
That is to say, there seems to be a growing conviction in large sections of the population that before their actions were the same ideas as the social elites that have hitherto prevailed, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the general sense of the term, had made their own time and were increasingly alien to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership, in short, undergroundly fuels a branching but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political establishments, which is manifested in the sudden electoral "riots" or sudden changes in the collective mood of recent and very recent times, from the rise of conservatism in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of the Labour consensus in Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
It seems that the traditional elites, their parties, their programmes, but also their rituals, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats, some would say, are finding it increasingly difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not yet taking shape in the deepest layers of Western societies and which the economic crisis is revitalizing, increasing, potentially stirring up.
In the face of all this, to say that a 'mass rebellion' is on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes open is certainly not.
