When the energy comes from the waves now the big ones come in.
It's an uncontacted deposit, covering over 70% of the planet's surface, and now it's being discovered by the world's big energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable resources that they've set their eyes on, and now they're trying to get their hands on, giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movement of the sea has been studied for over a hundred years, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now environmental concerns and the new oil boom are giving the sector a boost.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be met by offshore wind turbines.
This would be twice as much as is currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there'd be the currents and the tides.
Colossus on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which signed an agreement in 2005 to build a plant in the north of Portugal.
When the deal was announced, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies are betting on marine energy, and among these companies there is a tradition of traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies", a spokesman for a company affiliated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is considering cooperating with us".
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the US Energy Commission for a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is a significant sign, especially when you consider that the United States is still extracting oil in Alaska and that President Bush recently launched a plan for new drilling.
